segments.text: The following is an interview with Mr. Coulter Hoppus, distinguished lawyer and longtime resident of the Bryan College Station area.
The interview is being recorded in Mr. Hoppus's office, which is located in the Virisco building in downtown Bryan.
The interviewer is John O'Hara, and the date is March 30, 1976.
To begin with, I'd like to thank you for letting me come and interview you.
What we're trying to do is find out something about the early...
This works as a microphone?
Yes.
Okay.
What we're trying to do is get some information about the early inhabitants of Bryan.
Between John O'Hara and Coper Hoppus, conducted in the office of Coper Hoppus in the Briscoe building in Bryan, Texas, at 5 o'clock p.m. of the afternoon of March 30th, 1976, right?
And the purpose of this interview is to get background information on early historical facts relating to Bryan and College Station and Brazos County, Texas.
Okay, we'll go from there.
To begin with, could you tell me when and where you were born?
I was born in Hill County, Texas, in Hillsboro, in 1910, October 1910.
Do you know where the Hoppus family came to Texas from?
My father came to Texas from Arkansas, northeastern Arkansas.
And they settled in Hill County?
Not immediately.
He was at many places in Texas working for the railroad.

He came here during the time the railroads were being expanded and eventuated as being a station agent in Hillsboro for the Trinity and Brazos Valley Railroad, which was derogatorily referred to as the Bow Wheel.
You, of course, didn't enjoy all that, but practically all railroads
had various names that were applied to them, most of which related to the rather long names which they adopted.
Is that the railroad that comes through here now?
Is that the same?
No, no.
This railroad has since merged with Burlington, I believe, and the nearest place that comes to Bryant is North Zuch, which is east of here.
But they, like the Missouri, Kansas, and Texas is called Acadia, you know.
Yeah, well, that's a railroad in Georgia called the Tallulah Falls and something and of course on all the cars it had TF and something.
It wasn't a very good railroad and it came out as a total failure.
This was quite a common in the time, Red Road building.
Do you know what year it was when it first came to Texas?
My father?
No, I do not.
When did he move to Bryan?
He never did move to Bryan.
No.
What caused your family to come to Bryan?
My family didn't come to Bryan.
I came to Bryan.
I was orphaned and was brought here.
be reared by a grandmother when I was 12 years old.
Can you tell me something about what Brian was like or what you can first remember about Brian when you came?
Well, yes, I can remember
good many things about it.
Primarily the only difference now and then has been a rather large expansion of the residential community in a southeasterly direction towards
College Station or towards A&M University.
The time I came here as a little boy, well, Texas A&M University was much more remote from Bryan than it is today, or Bryan was much more remote from it.
There was not a city of any kind at College Station.
or any surrounding residential areas.
The professors almost totally, when possible, lived on the campus in houses furnished by the university, by the college as it was called then.
Other workers lived in Brown,
The primary access was what is now called College Road.
It was a county road that went on out there and automobiles were used to some extent.
But automobiles were not generally owned or very popular in the early 1920s.
They were just beginning to be used.
on a utilitarian basis.
Up to that time, they had been pretty well playthings or sports things.
Did they ever have trolley trains here?
Yes.
There was an electric interurban railroad that ran from the Ursuline Academy, which is basically northeast, on the northeast edge of Bryan, or the eastern edge of Bryan, which is no longer there.

down Ursuline Avenue, as it's called, and thence into downtown Bryan, thence out College Avenue, which is now partially Texas Avenue, to what now is called the Y, where actually Texas Avenue goes south and east and College Road goes south,

and about where Woodson Lumber Company now situated and at that point the Interurban Railroad track took off cross country to Texas A&M University and stopped or had the station at the north what is now the north gate of Texas A&M and the right of way
The route that it followed is now Cabot Avenue.
In fact, the right-of-way that was owned by the Interurban Railroad was acquired by the city of Brown to use as a street.
When did it cease to run its route?
I never know that there was a... About 1922.
It ceased?
was having difficulty, and I believe finally switched over totally to buses in 1927.
That's kind of off the top of my head, but I believe that finally went totally to a bus system in 1927.
The buses ran more or less the same way?
No, the buses ran, of course, on the streets that were available.
How large was the city when Perth came under it?
Do you have any idea?
I would say about 5,000 people in 1920.
Was it mainly around what is now the downtown area?
No, I don't know just how to describe it, but it was about in the same...

to a degree the same confirmation as it is now with the exception of all of the tremendous residential growth that has occurred along Highway 6 which has become Texas Avenue and to the east, south and east of that.
What were the main business areas?
What?
What were the main business areas?
Has it been downtown most of the time?
Yes, Main Street and the courthouse area was the main business area at that time.
What has been the main business area?
Well, of course, in the very beginning, the agricultural enterprise of the area was the primary business.
The cotton in the valley?
Well, both on the hill and in the valley, too.
I mean, there was a tremendous outbreak of cotton all over the country along about
World War I days when they were seeking the cellulose of cotton to make gunpowder.

And this continued until about 1925 when there was a combination of a market crash and a drought and crop failure and I don't know what all and it's been somewhat declining since that time according to my visualization.

I could not categorize and it would not be correct in my mind to say that Texas A&M University has been the business of the main business of Bryan but I don't think there's ever been any doubt of what the funds that have been used or the funds that were brought into the area by the
Texas A&M College and its affiliated agencies and have been expended here have certainly constituted a major portion of the economic base of the community.
Do you think that the university has contributed more
Oh, I think that there's no question.
I think all business research studies and everything will show that the so-called local expenditures of the university
is the largest, by many millions of dollars, the largest injection of funds into the economy in the community.
And of course, and that doesn't, of course, they multiply themselves through the use of individual people.
I may get back to what you were talking about.
Where did you go to school?
What school?
Baylor University at Waco.
Okay, I mean, beginning with the elementary school and the high school.
Well, there were only two.
The present Bowie School was called the Westside Elementary School, and the present Fannin School was called the Eastside Elementary School and Brown High School.
Yes, no, the high school was on where Fannin is now, and was located in the same building as there.
And incidentally, that's the same property that the first school ever built in Bryan was on, on that property at the corner of the 29th and Baker.
That was the portion of the city that was set aside for a school by the
Texas Town Lot Company that originally surveyed the city.
I went on and did both my undergraduate work and my graduate law work at Baylor.
After I got to Baylor.
Oh yes, I
I'm very proud of my profession.
Very few people, I think, can get a proper perspective of what the practice of law is about.
But what we are actually engaged in is the administration of justice.
And I assure you that no society can long exist without it.
Now, whether or not
We're doing it acceptably at this time, might be argued on an individual basis, but we have no other way to settle controversy between individual members of our society.
And that has to be provided in some form.
When you were growing up and now, has there ever been a lot of crime running on the station, or has it been mostly small publics and things like that?
Has there ever been a great quantity of crime?
If it was, I was not aware of it.
We certainly had...
crime from time to time, but I was simply not conscious of it, though I was not protected from it, not as an adult, and in a small town, of course, not even as a child.
Has there ever been any, I don't really know how to put it, civil rights
with the black minority in Bryan.
Any trouble with that here at all?
Have you ever felt any trouble in Bryan over that issue?
No.
Certainly there have been petitions and discussions more recently.
By that I mean in the last 20 years.
But...
it's very difficult to communicate and of course i assume that any real militant militant could attack us but in truth in fact we have always had according to my uh evaluation
a rather responsible and sensitive group of people in both what is now referred to as the white community and the black community.
When I first came to Bryan, well, the so-called Negro Elementary School
was located on Washington Avenue.
It was called Washington School and maybe it was on Houston Street, but it was a very attractive building.
It had won two National Architectural Awards and was really a building and
that was superior to, equal to, or superior to the other elementary schools.
Shortly, as it became necessary, the Kemp High School was built.
And we simply did not have second grade schools for the black community here.
Brian was very fortunate.

has been in both the white and the black area in that in about 1919 they purchased the electric utilities for the specific purpose of financing the schools and a lot of people don't know it now but of course state financing and federal funding was not available
until 1948 when the Gilmer-Akin bill was first passed in Texas.

And during the so-called Depression of 1929 through about 1934, virtually all the school districts, not just in Texas but in the United States, could not pay any, they had no money to pay anybody anyway.
They paid in what was called script, which was just a promissory note that someday if they got some money, they'd pay.
People just had to survive as best they could.
But because of the electric utility funding in Bryan, well, there was cash money available.
pay teachers, and as a consequence, the ability to recruit the top quality was remarkable.
During that same period of time, the state of Texas couldn't pay any salary.
The state employees received script, but not the teachers at A&M because they were being paid out of the
public school funds, which came from the public lands of Texas, the public school lands.
But regular state offices got paid in script.
Those that were dependent upon tax revenue, because nobody paid any taxes in that period of time.
Well, supposedly they didn't.
But in any event, this built a tremendous stack

of teachers and particularly in the black schools and we have just always had real good communications between whites and blacks here I feel and we had good schools perhaps not as good as they should have been I don't know but I know that
They were certainly not downgraded or disregarded.
And we integrated our high school here, I believe, within a year after Brown v. School Board was decided.
Because I was a member of the school board, and I took a copy of the Supreme Court opinion that Brown v. School Board distributed to my fellow members.

told him i said i mean there was a lot of talk at that time it's not going to be i mean over the south they were saying well we're not going to do it and all like that i told him i said forget about it it's here it has already happened there's no arguing with it so we ought to get with it and we started attempting to identify at that time
black students in the black system that could, without any difficulty or problem to themselves, move into the Stephen F. Austin High School was called in and started doing it.
We were in the process of integrating the high school here long before many, many, many places even gave it any consideration.
Also, black people have always been able to borrow money in this community.
That's something that very few people know about.
I don't ever remember a time that a responsible black individual couldn't obtain bank credit, the very best credit.
He didn't have to go to a backstreet shyster loan company.
He could go talk to the chief loan officer of any bank in this community.
I've seen it happen many, many times.
I know that I have waited in line to see a loan officer while blacks preceded me, and it was not offensive to me, and as far as I know, it was never offensive to anyone.
I know what's now the first banking for us was the first state bank.
It was located here on Main Street.
The building's still standing.
Right inside the main door was a very long wooden settee

and it was referred to here as the mourners bench and then Mr. Higgs and Mr. Delaney the two vice presidents and the main loan officers of the bank sat right there immediately visible to everyone behind a rail and the customary practice and everybody did it was to go in and take your place in line on the mourners bench or stand in line and then
Man at the head of the bench went next.
Well, my family owned substantial stock in the bank.
In fact, my uncle was the president of it.
Did not have offices in it.
But I transacted my business like that, just like everybody else, and it was not...
I mean, it was just normal.
The bond building and loan from the day it was organized.

has always accepted applications and from black people for loans for the building of homes and has has always had a tremendous part of its clientele were responsible black people that could qualify for loans so i think these things contributed i mean it created good communications
It's always seemed to me that there's been very good relations.
I've lived here since probably 57.
And I've never noticed any trouble whatsoever.
There have been places, there'd be a fight or something like that, but that happens everywhere.
But it always seems that everyone gets along pretty well.

well i think there are reasons for that and i think they were built in many many many years ago but uh the uh like the primary thing was that i guess that there was just real good communications that primarily that the
that it was an open society, that blacks were never closed off as such.
Certainly, I mean, they followed the, our social patterns were identically the same as they were everywhere else in the United States.
